# SQLMesh Conventions

> **This rule covers SQLMesh projects** — internal Exodus projects or client engagements using SQLMesh as their transformation framework.
> For dbt Core projects (Foundation, ironlayer_infra, client templates), see `dbt-sql.mdc`.
> For dbt Cloud Enterprise client engagements, see `dbt-cloud.mdc`.

---

## When This Rule Applies

You are working in a **SQLMesh** context when:
- A `config.yaml`, `config.yml`, or `config.py` file is present in the project root
- Model `.sql` files contain `MODEL (` DDL blocks
- Model `.py` files use `@model` decorators with `is_sql=True` or return DataFrames
- The client or project explicitly uses SQLMesh as the transformation framework

**Auto-detection signal:** `ironlayer plan --framework auto` detects SQLMesh by checking for `config.yaml` + `MODEL()` blocks in `.sql` files.

---

## SQLMesh vs dbt — When to Use Which

| Factor | Choose dbt | Choose SQLMesh |
|--------|-----------|---------------|
| Team familiarity | Existing dbt expertise | New project or greenfield |
| Cloud managed service | dbt Cloud Enterprise available | Prefer open-source only |
| Dev environments | OK with ephemeral Databricks schemas | Want free Virtual Data Environments |
| Data validation | OK with custom IronLayer diff (I-19) | Want built-in Table Diff and data contracts |
| SQL transpilation | Single dialect | Multi-dialect (Redshift → Databricks, etc.) |
| Python models | Not needed | Need Python macros or DataFrame transforms |
| State management | Manual incremental logic | Want SQLMesh automatic state tracking |

